commit_list.message:
Support additional lookups, use Launch Services version numbers

Add support for querying the default application, as well as querying
handlers of a given URL.

Replace use of the CFBundleVersion as written with the Launch Services
intepretation of the version number. This requires use of a private API,
but provides a more accurate version comparison for the application's
intended purpose - identifying duplicate bundles with the same version.
Launch Services parses the string and creates its own representation of
the version number that may discard additional information in the
string, so a simple string comparison is inappropriate.

commit_list.message:
Use the project's deployment target when building Clang

This is accomplished by preserving the MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET
environment variable in the cleaned environment. In the absence of an
explicit -mmacosx-version-min argument Clang will read the value of this
environment variable determine the deployment target.

The --enable-libcpp option is also passed to LLVM's configure script.

Defer reading the expansion location until needed

over those in system headers. Profiling revealed

reading of the expansion location until an associated property is read

obtaining the expansion location for the tens of thousands of
declarations in system headers.

when visiting the cursors of a translation unit. In situations where
only a subset of the cursors are of interest, such as those not in
system headers, the work done to create these strings in the initializer
slows down the application unecessarily. Lazily load these properties as
well to remove this overhead.

commit_list.message:
Add support for listing item types other than dictionaries

Although the /content-codes endpoint reports that the mlit code is of
the list type (12), this is not always the case. For example, the
daap.browseartistlisting type uses mlit fields with string data. To
handle these messages a parser needs to be aware of the parent context
as well as the content-code to determine what type of data is expected
for the mlit code.

To accomplish this the dmap_field structure is modified to include an
additional DMAP_TYPE field storing the expected type of the listing item
children. Parsing is moved to a dmap_parse_internal() function that
receives a pointer to the parent dmap_field, if any. Upon encountering
an mlit field the parent field's list_item_type is used to parse the
listing item. If a listing item type is not specified a list/dictionary
is assumed.

commit_list.message:
Associate generated classes with the unit test bundle

This is accomplished by implementing the undocumented +bundleForClass
for the generated classes. This isn't necessary for proper operation,
but it results in more expected output from XCTest reports. With this
change Google Test classes appear to be part of the unit test bundle
that GoogleTests.mm is compiled into, as they did under earlier
implementations. Without it tests are still executed and filtered
properly, but appear in the report as part of a separate bundle for the
application running tests. When run within Xcode this is a command line
app so the bundle is represented as the name of the directory where that
app is located ("Agents").
commit_list.repo_description: Google Test integration with Xcode

commit_list.message:
Support Xcode 7 by generating classes for each Google Test case

This was considered for prior implementations but avoided to simplify
the implementation and eliminate the risk of a generated class name
conflicting with an existing class. Originally XCTest's reporting and
Xcode integration supported this well, but in Xcode 6 parts of the
framework expected that test suite names corresponded to actual
Objective-C classes and test method names corresponded to instance
methods of those classes. Still, it was possible to work around this by
implementing undocumented XCTestCase methods that controlled the
reported class and method names for a test.

With Xcode 7 this workaround is no longer possible. The implementation
of test filtering has been made more efficient, but in a way that breaks
filtering compatibility with test suites added via +[XCTestCase
defaultTestSuite]. In prior releases the test set was built by locating
all XCTestCase subclasses, calling defaultTestSuite on them, then
filtering the results. Now the implementation assumes that it can pass
the test suite name to NSClassFromString() and directly obtain a class
already populated with methods for each test name in that suite. This is
not the case for test suites created via defaultTestSuite.

To continue to support filtering, treating Google Test cases as peers,
and to reduce conflicts with the XCTest framework, generate Objective-C
classes for each Google Test case and populate them with Objective-C
methods corresponding to each test in the Google Test case. The classes
are also given a custom implementation of +[XCTestCase testInvocations]
that returns test invocations for every method in the class.
Alternatively the generated methods could be prefixed with "test" to
allow XCTest to detect them automatically, but this could lead to
awkward test names if a Google Test name already starts with "test".

An alternative implementation for Xcode 7 compatibility would be to
sacrifice representing Google Tests as peers to standard XCTest suites
and instead represent them all as methods under an XCTestCase instance,
like "-[GoogleTests TestSuiteName.TestCaseName]". To support filtering
+[XCTestCase testCaseWithSelector:] could be overridden to recognize a
name following this pattern and return an appropriate XCTestCase
instance capable of running the test.

An additional note is that in Xcode 7 XCTest will instantiate an
instance of an NSPrincipalClass specified in the test bundle before
searching for tests. This could be used as an alternative to observing
the NSBundleDidLoadNotification for our own bundle.

commit_list.message:
Filter out disabled tests unless instructed not to

Google Test does not provide a way of filtering tests before they are
run. As a result, at the time +defaultTestSuite is called Google Test
does not yet think that tests prefixed with DISABLED_ are actually
disabled. While these tests are not run unless enabled via
--gtest_also_run_disabled_tests, the XCTest output gives the appearance
that they are run. Address this by checking for DISABLED_ tests
ourselves and excluding them unless the also_run_disabled_tests flag has
been set.

commit_list.message:
Support Xcode 6 and filtering via XCTest

Rather than exposing a single XCTestCase to XCTest that runs all Google
Tests at once, create an XCTestCase for each Google test that runs just
that Google test via RUN_ALL_TESTS(). This integrates better with the
XCTest framework, allowing it to perform test filtering automatically.

This also adds support for Xcode 6 by removing the use of the deprecated
XCTest method for reporting test failures, and by adding support for the
testClassName and testMethodName methods.

commit_list.message:
Work around Clang issue with forward declaration a class or protocol

Clang returns the first declaration of an Objective-C class or protocol
as the canonical declaration. As a result a forward declaration of one
of these types that appears before the actual declaration is incorrectly
considered the canonical declaration. This breaks our isEqual: test
meant to ensure that we only consider the canonical declaration part of
the API. To work around the issue, check for one of these types by
comparing the cursor kind. Only the real canonical declaration will have
a cursor kind of one of these types.

commit_list.message:
Add support for comparing platform SDKs

All frameworks in the SDK are compared, with the exception of a few
macOS frameworks that cannot be parsed simply by including all headers
or the framework's umbrella header. The contents of /usr/include are
also not included, as these headers must be included in specific orders.
Using module maps would likely enable these to be included in the
future.

System frameworks are symlinked to a temporary directory and parsed with
a framework search path for this directory. This enables the fast
isInSystemHeader check to be used to exclude other system headers
outside the framework.

When a platform SDK or a framework within a platform SDK is given as one
of the API paths to compare appropriate sysroot and deployment targets
are added to the compiler arguments automatically if not explicitly
specified.

category has on the API (e.g., extending the list of protocols a class
conforms to).

Categories on classes from other modules are still reported.

Add workaround for exclusion of builtin function declarations

Clang has an issue with declarations for functions that exist in its
builtin function database (e.g., NSLog, objc_msgSend). The canonical
cursor for these functions has an identical source location as the
declaration in the file we're parsing, but an extent that covers only
the function's name, so libclang does not consider them equal. Add a
workaround for this case and test to verify that such function
declarations are included.
